# PROJECT SPECIFICATION
 ## OMF Onepager Site Specification

### Overall Structure:

- **Navigation:** Sticky menu either at the top or side, allowing direct section access.
- **Clearly Defined Sections:** Smooth vertical scroll with subtle visual effects for section separation (soft shadows or background color changes).
- **GIFs and Demos:** Integrated within each section for clear demonstrations. GIFs should be concise (10-15 sec) and focused.
- **Visual Style:** Minimalist design with a clear background, readable fonts (Roboto or similar), and vibrant accents to highlight key points.

---

### Proposed Sections and Content:

#### 1\. What's OMF?
- **Brief Text:** "OMF is an open-source framework designed to simplify the robust and efficient development of MagicDraw plugins. Built by developers for developers, OMF streamlines complex automations reliably and elegantly."
- **Image:** Clean and minimalist OMF logo accompanied by the tagline "Build Smarter, Not Harder."
- **GIF/Demo:** Quick demo showcasing feature creation and activation live in MagicDraw (~8s).

#### 2\. Core: Robustness and Simplicity
- **Short Explanatory Text:** "At OMF's core is the OMFBarrier, ensuring robust error management with automatic rollback upon failure. Combined with FeatureRegisterer and integrated listeners, managing your plugin state becomes straightforward."
- **GIF:** Execution showcasing a forced error, automatic rollback, and restoration (~10s).
- **Short Code Example:** Simple snippet illustrating barrier declaration.

#### 3\. Feature-Oriented Architecture
- **Text:** "OMF structures your plugins into modular, autonomous Features, enhancing scalability and simplifying maintenance."
- **Image/Diagram:** Simplified visual diagram illustrating feature-oriented architecture with highlighted inter-feature interactions.
- **GIF:** Live demonstration of enabling/disabling Features (~12s).

#### 4\. Feature Items: UIAction, LiveAction, Option, Hook, API
- **Text:** "OMF provides ready-to-use Feature Items. Easily integrate UI actions, live actions, configurable options, custom hooks, and standardized APIs."
- **Grid of GIFs:**
   - UIAction: Button click in MagicDraw UI.
   - LiveAction: Immediate response to model modifications.
   - Option: Real-time configuration change.
   - Hook: Adding custom behaviors triggered by events.

#### 5\. Library: SysML Factory, SysML Helpers, LayoutManager
- **Text:** "Accelerate your development with a powerful library: effortlessly create SysML elements, manipulate them efficiently, and automatically manage visual layouts."
- **GIF:** Dynamic example showing automated SysML block creation and automatic layout adjustments (~12s).

#### 6\. Feature Library: Organizer, Stereotypes, FlowCreation
- **Text:** "Access a comprehensive collection of built-in Features for organizing projects, managing stereotypes, or automating flow creation."
- **GIFs:**
   - Organizer: Quick sorting and filtering elements.
   - Stereotypes: Instant add/remove stereotype with immediate effect.
   - FlowCreation: Full flow automation demo (~15s).

#### 7\. Functional Test Framework: Model Comparison & Scenario Testing
- **Text:** "Automatically test your plugins using the integrated functional test framework. Efficiently compare SysML models and simulate user scenarios to ensure reliability."
- **GIF:** Quick demonstration of automated SysML model comparison with highlighted results (~12s).

---

### GitHub README
- **GIF Compatibility:** Yes, GitHub supports GIFs in READMEs, perfect for concise and effective demonstrations directly accessible from your repository.
- **Suggestion:** Clearly link your onepager website from your README with key GIFs to attract developers at first glance.

This specification highlights OMF with visually appealing content emphasizing technical efficiency and clear explanations, directly targeting demanding developers.


#Coding Process
- new features shall be implemented in a new branch, named like the feature.
- test shall be added for the new feature.
- documentation shall be added for the new feature.
- architecture documentation shall be updated to reflect the new changes.
- the branch shall be pushed to the remote repository.
- a PR shall be created for the branch, and merged into the main branch.
- the branch shall be deleted after the PR is merged.

#Chat verbosity
- Be concise, to the point, and clear.
- Be creative on UI/UX design, make it simple and intuitive, modern and chearfull.
- Explain any Backend concepts, as well as the reasoning behind the code.

#Debugging
- Always use the test access components to debug the code.
- Always make an analysis of the potential root cause of the issue, instead of just fixing the symptom.
- Always consider the impact of the changes on the other parts of the code.

#Code Documentation
- Always update code comments when editing code.
- Always add a top comment explaining the purpose of the file
- Always add comments to the code to explain "why" behind the code in more complex functions.
- Always add comments to the code to explain "how" behind the code in more complex functions.
- Always comment the main REST API endpoints.
- Always add a comment before the main react div explaining the structure of the div
- always add comment explaining the css properties

#Project Documentation
- Always update the project documentation when editing code.
- Always add a top comment explaining the purpose of the project

#Start/Stop script
- provide a set of script to start Back and Front end, and to stop them.

#Important 
- DO NOT DUPLICATE CODE, if you see code that is similar, refactor it into a function or a class.
- DO NOT HALLUCINATE CODE, if you don't know the answer, say so instead of guessing.
- DO NOT TOUCH ANYTHING OUTSIDE THE PROJECT FOLDER, unless explicitly told to do so.
- ALWAYS MAKE ANALYSIS OF THE CODE BEFORE WRITING ANYTHING.
- ALWAYS CONSULT THE PROJECT DOCUMENTATION BEFORE WRITING ANYTHING.


Memory:
 
- When you need to remember something, update the .cursormemory.md file.
- Refer to the .cursormemory.md file to view the memory.
- Update the memory with project specifications, requirements, flow of the code, and other relevant information.
- Add instructions for development like how to add new GraphQL mutations and queries to the memory.
 
Planning:
 
- Always plan the code before writing it.
- Think about how the new code will fit into the existing codebase.
- Think about how the new code will interact with the other parts of the codebase.
- Think about how the new code will handle errors and edge cases.
- Think about how the new code will be used by the frontend.
- Think about how the new code will be used by the users.
- Think about how the new code will be used by the developers.